  "prompt": "If you want to go to graduate school in biophysics, should you major in physics or biology?",
  "response": "When considering a path to graduate school in biophysics, both physics and biology are relevant undergraduate majors, and the choice depends on your interests and career goals. Here are some factors to consider for each:\n\n1. **Physics Major:**\n   - **Pros:** A strong foundation in physics will provide you with critical analytical skills, mathematical proficiency, and an understanding of the physical principles underlying biological systems. This is particularly advantageous if you are interested in the theoretical or computational aspects of biophysics.\n   - **Cons:** You might have less exposure to biological concepts and laboratory techniques, which are also important in biophysics research.\n\n2. **Biology Major:**\n   - **Pros:** Starting with a biology major allows you to gain a deep understanding of biological systems, processes, and laboratory skills. This is beneficial if you are interested in experimental biophysics or applying physical principles to solve biological problems.\n   - **Cons:** You may have less training in the mathematical and physical principles that are integral to more quantitative or theoretical areas in biophysics.\n\n3. **Integrated or Interdisciplinary Programs:**\n   - Some universities offer interdisciplinary programs that combine physics and biology, or even specific biophysics majors. These programs might provide a balanced education tailored to a future in biophysics.\n\nUltimately, the best choice depends on your interests and aspirations. If you're leaning more towards theoretical and quantitative aspects, a physics major might be more suitable. If you're more interested in experimental work and biological systems, biology might be the better option. Regardless of your major, you should seek opportunities to take courses from both fields, gain relevant research experience, and develop strong computational skills.",
